*Rankings reflect [[2007-08 NCAA Division I men's basketball rankings#ESPN/USA Today Coaches Poll|Coaches Poll]] as of March 3, 2008

====Out of conference games====
Notre Dame opened the season with a win at home against the Long Island Blackbirds.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=273160087|title=Notre Dame 82, Long Island U. 50|date=November 12, 2007|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> They next traveled to the [[U.S. Virgin Islands]] to face the Monmouth Hawks in the first round of the [[Paradise Jam Tournament]]. After beating the Hawks,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=273200087|title=Notre Dame 76, Monmouth, N.J. 33|date=November 16, 2007|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> they went on to lose in the [[semifinals]] to the Baylor Bears,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=273220239|title=Baylor 68, Notre Dame 64|publisher=ESPN|date=November 18, 2007|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> and lose in the [[Third place playoff|third place game]] to the Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets to leave the tournament with a 2&ndash;2 record.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=273230087|title=Georgia Tech 70, Notre Dame 69|publisher=ESPN|date=November 19, 2007|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> The Irish returned home for three games and went on to win against the Youngstown State Penguins,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=273280087|title=Notre Dame 87, Youngstown St. 75|publisher=ESPN|date=November 24, 2007|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> the Colgate Raiders,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=273300087|title=Notre Dame 94, Colgate 63|publisher=ESPN|date=November 26, 2007|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> and the Eastern Michigan Eagles,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=273350087|title=Notre Dame 76, E. Michigan 65|publisher=ESPN|date=December 1, 2007|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> to move to 5&ndash;2 on the season.

They next traveled to New York to face the Kansas State Wildcats in the Jimmy V. Classic, their first televised game of the season. After a close first half, Notre Dame pulled away to get the win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=273380087|title=Norte Dame shuts down K-State leader Beasley in second half|publisher=ESPN|date=December 4, 2007|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> Returning home once again, they beat the Northern Illinois Huskies before taking two weeks off for [[final exam]]s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=273420087|title=Notre Dame 108, N. Illinois 62|publisher=ESPN|date=December 8, 2007|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> After finals, they played three more home games, beating the San Francisco Dons,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=273560087|title=Notre Dame 84, San Francisco 76|publisher=ESPN|date=December 22, 2007|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> the Brown Bears,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=273630087|title=Notre Dame 87, Brown 54|publisher=ESPN|date=December 29, 2007|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> and the North Florida Ospreys,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=273650087|title=Notre Dame 77, North Florida 58|publisher=ESPN|date=December 31, 2007|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> to finish their non-conference schedule with a 10&ndash;2 record.

====Big East games====
Notre Dame began their conference play with two home games before the students returned from [[Christmas break]]. With wins over the West Virginia Mountaineers and the Connecticut Huskies,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280030087|title=Notre Dame 69, West Virginia 56|publisher=ESPN|date=January 3, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280050087|title=Notre Dame 73, Connecticut 67|publisher=ESPN|date=January 5, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> they began conference play with a 2&ndash;0 record. They next traveled to face the 16<sup>th</sup>-ranked Marquette Golden Eagles for their first true road game of the season, however they lost by 26&nbsp;points to give Mike Brey his worst loss as Notre Dame coach.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280120269|title=Marquette hands Notre Dame most lopsided defeat in rivalry history|publisher=ESPN|date=January 12, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> The team returned home to beat the Cincinnati Bearcats,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280150087|title=Notre Dame 91, Cincinnati 74|publisher=ESPN|date=January 15, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> before once again losing on the road against the sixth-ranked Georgetown Hoyas.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280190046|title=Georgetown defense stifles Irish shooting in win|publisher=ESPN|date=January 19, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> They finally got their first road win a week later against the 18<sup>th</sup>-ranked Villanova Wildcats to move to 4&ndash;2 in the Big East with a 14&ndash;4 overall record.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280260222|title=McAlarney leads Notre Dame past slumping Villanova|publisher=ESPN|date=January 26, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref>

Notre Dame next returned home to face the Providence Friars, and, although the Friars were 3&ndash;4 in conference play, the game stayed close and the Irish only won after an [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] period.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280310087|title=Notre Dame 81, Providence 74|publisher=ESPN|date=January 31, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> They continued at home and beat DePaul in the first of two games against the Blue Demons,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280330087|title=Notre Dame 89, DePaul 80|publisher=ESPN|date=February 2, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> to move into the rankings for the first time in the season. As the 21<sup>st</sup>-ranked team in the country, the team traveled to Seton Hall to face the Pirates. They got their second road win of the season,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280372550|title=Notre Dame nets big conference win against Seton Hall|publisher=ESPN|date=February 6, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> and returned home to face 16<sup>th</sup>-ranked Marquette once again. With a win over the Golden Eagles,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280400087|title=Fighting Irish keep home streak going with free throws|publisher=ESPN|date=February 9, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> they moved up to 18<sup>th</sup> in the rankings. They next traveled to Connecticut to face the 17<sup>th</sup>-ranked Huskies for the second time. Although the Irish led for much of the game, they lost in the end.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280440041|title=Connecticut snaps Notre Dame's five-game winning streak|publisher=ESPN|date=February 13, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> Despite winning another road game later in the week against the Rutgers Scarlet Knights,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280480164|title=No. 18 Fighting Irish hold off reeling Rutgers|publisher=ESPN|date=February 17, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> they dropped back to 21<sup>st</sup> in the rankings with a 19&ndash;5 record overall.

The Irish next returned home to face the Pittsburgh Panthers who had beaten them in five straight games. Although trailing at [[half-time]], Notre Dame came back and scored 52&nbsp;points in the second half to win the game.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280520087|title=No. 21 Irish use late 21-10 run to drop Panthers|publisher=ESPN|date=February 21, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-23}}</ref> The team stayed at home to play the Syracuse Orange and led the whole game to get another conference win,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280550087|title=McAlarney hits school-best nine 3s as ND wins 36th straight at home|publisher=ESPN|date=February 24, 2008|accessdate=2008-02-24}}</ref> however lost another away game the same week at the 18<sup>th</sup>-ranked Louisville Cardinals.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280590097|title=Padgett scores 26 to push Louisville past Notre Dame|date=February 28, 2008|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=2008-02-28}}</ref> They next traveled to face DePaul, and with the win, swept the Blue Demons in the season.<ref name="DePaul2">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280620305|title=Harangody, Notre Dame withstand furious DePaul rally|publisher=ESPN|date=March 2, 2008|accessdate=2008-03-02}}</ref> The Irish returned home for their final home game of the season, and, although were held to under 69&nbsp;points for only the fifth time in the season, beat the St. John's Red Storm.<ref name="St. Johns">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280650087|title=Irish become first Big East team to go undefeated at home two straight seasons|publisher=ESPN|date=March 5, 2008|accessdate=2008-03-06}}</ref> For their final regular season game they traveled to South Florida and defeated the Bulls to win their fourteenth Big East game, a school record.<ref name="USF">{{cite news|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280680058|title=Notre Dame scores school-best 14th Big East win|publisher=ESPN|date=March 8, 2008|accessdate=2008-03-09}}</ref> With a 14&ndash;4 record in the Big East, Notre Dame finished the regular season tied in second in the conference with Louisville.

==Post season tournaments==
===Big East Tournament===
{{main|2008 Big East Men's Basketball Tournament}}
With Marquette's loss to Georgetown on March 1,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280610269|title=Hibbert, Wallace score 20 each to lift Georgetown in OT|date=March 1, 2008|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=2008-03-03}}</ref> and Notre Dame's win over DePaul on March 2, the Irish clinched a [[bye (sports)|bye]] in the first round of the [[Big East Men's Basketball Tournament]].<ref name="DePaul2" /> They played their opening game, as the third seed of the tournament,<ref name="USF" /> on March 13 at [[Madison Square Garden]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/champweek2008/news/story?page=ncb_champweek2008#bigeast|title=Conference tournament schedules, results|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=2008-03-03}}</ref> Marquette, the sixth seed in the tournament, defeated Seton Hall in the first round to advance and play the Irish in the second round.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280720269|title=Marquette holds Seton Hall scoreless in final minutes of win|publisher=ESPN|date=March 12, 2008|accessdate=2008-03-14}}</ref> Despite leading scorer, Luke Harangody, only playing for seven minutes in the first half, the Irish held a six point lead at half-time. However, late in the second half Marquette took a 10&nbsp;point lead, the largest of the game, and held on to the lead for the 89&ndash;79 win, dropping Notre Dame out of the tournament.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/recap?gameId=280730087|title=McNeal's career-high 28 carry Marquette to Big East semis|publisher=ESPN|date=March 13, 2008|accessdate=2008-03-14}}</ref>

===NCAA Tournament===
{{main|2008 NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Tournament}}
Although teams are not officially invited to the [[NCAA Men's Division I Basketball Championship|NCAA Tournament]] until [[Selection Sunday]] (March 16, 2008), multiple publications predicted before the selection that the Irish would receive an [[at-large bid]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Hamilton, Brian|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/chi-16-notre-dame-basketballmar16,1,2936821.story|title=Notre Dame awaits NCAA seeding|publisher=Chicago Tribune|date=March 16, 2008|accessdate=2008-03-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Parrish, Gary|url=http://cbs.sportsline.com/collegebasketball/story/10639109|title=Projecting the Field|publisher=CBSSportsline|accessdate=2008-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Mandel, Stewart|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/writers/stewart_mandel/03/03/bubble.watch/index.html?eref=T1|title=Clearer at top|publisher=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=2008-03-03}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Burlison, Frank|url=http://msn.foxsports.com/cbk/story/7856334/Breaking-the-Bracket:-Just-two-weeks-left|title=Breaking the Bracket: Just two weeks left|publisher=Fox Sports|accessdate=2008-03-03}}</ref> The NCAA announced that the team would receive a five seed in the tournament and face the George Mason Patriots in Denver on March 20, whom they beat.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ncaa.com/basketball-mens/article.aspx?id=141568|title=Bracket Announced!|publisher=NCAA.com|date=March 16, 2008|accessdate=2008-03-16}}</ref> The Irish went on to play [[Washington State Cougars men's basketball|Washington State]], to whom they lost.

==Statistics==
As a team, Notre Dame averages over 80&nbsp;points per game and have a 45.9% [[field goal percentage]]. Top scorer, Luke Harangody, averages over 20&nbsp;points and 10&nbsp;rebounds per game, a [[double-double]]. At the end of the regular season, he led the Big East in scoring. Additionally, he was second in the conference in [[Rebound (basketball)|rebounding]] and led the league in each category during conference play.<ref name="Awards">{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/basketball/ncaa/wires/03/11/2060.ap.bkc.big.east.awards.0300/|title=Notre Dame's Harangody and Brey sweep Big East postseason awards|publisher=Sports Illustrated|date=March 11, 2008|accessdate=2008-03-11}}</ref> Besides Harangody, two other players average over 10&nbsp;points per game, Kyle McAlarney and Rob Kurz. McAlarney also leads the conference in [[three-point field goal]] percentage.<ref name="KMac" /> Thirteen players have accumulated statistics in games for the Irish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncb/teams/stats?teamId=87|title=Notre Dame Fighting Irish Statistics - 2007-08|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=2008-03-07}}</ref>

