==After the season==
===Legacy===
Dating to February 2006, the Irish have won 37&nbsp;consecutive home games and 18&nbsp;Big East home games. The 18&nbsp;wins is the second longest streak in conference history,<ref>{{cite news|author=Coyne, Tom|url=http://www.courierpress.com/news/2008/feb/25/notre-dames-home-streak-reaches-36/|title=Notre Dame's home streak reaches 36|date=February 25, 2008|publisher=Evansville Courier & Press|accessdate=2008-03-03}}</ref> while the 36&nbsp;total wins is the second longest current streak in the country behind the [[BYU Cougars men's basketball|BYU Cougars]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Brown, Jake|url=http://nwitimes.com/articles/2008/02/25/sports/top_sports/doca4dbd58f269dd943862573f9007e9540.txt|title=Hot outside shooting carries ND past Syracuse|date=February 25, 2008|publisher=The Northwest Indiana and Illinois Times Newspaper|accessdate=2008-03-03}}</ref> With the win over St. John's on March 5, the Irish became the first Big East team to go undefeated at home in conference games in consecutive seasons.<ref name="St. Johns" />

===Award winners===
After the season ended, Luke Harangody was named the conference [[Big East Men's Basketball Player of the Year|Player of the Year]]. Additionally, Mike Brey was named conference Coach of the Year for the second year in a row.<ref name="Awards" />  Harangody was also named to the 1st Team All Big East squad, along with Kyle McAlarney.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bigeast.org/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=19400&ATCLID=1409119|title=2008 All-BIG EAST Men's Basketball Teams Announced|publisher=Big East Conference|date=March 10, 2008|accessdate=2008-03-12}}</ref>

===Transfers===
Notre Dame had two players transfer in following the season. Both will sit out the 2008-09 season per NCAA rules for transfer students.<ref name="Transfers in">{{cite press release|url=http://und.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/spec-rel/061708aaa.html |title= Ben Hansbrough And Scott Martin Join Irish Basketball Program |publisher=University of Notre Dame Athletic Department |date=2008-06-17 |accessdate=2008-10-23}}</ref>
* Scott Martin, a 6-8 [[swingman]], transferred after his freshman season at [[Purdue Boilermakers men's basketball|Purdue]]. Playing mainly off the bench, he averaged 8.5&nbsp;points and 3.8&nbsp;rebounds. He has three years of eligibility remaining.
* [[Ben Hansbrough]], a 6-3 [[guard (basketball)|guard]], transferred after his sophomore season at [[Mississippi State Bulldogs|Mississippi State]], and will have two years of eligibility at Notre Dame. The younger brother of [[North Carolina Tar Heels men's basketball|North Carolina]] superstar [[Tyler Hansbrough]], he comes off a sophomore season in which he averaged 10.5&nbsp;points, 3.8&nbsp;rebounds, and 2.6&nbsp;assists as a regular starter.

